"The present study was designed to investigate the effect of a novel compound, 1-[2-(4-chlorophenyl)ethyl]-4-(3-methylphenyl)-1H-imidazole (CPI), on the contractile response of guinea pig tracheal smooth muscle to histamine and acetylcholine. The experiments were performed on tracheal rings obtained from male and female guinea pigs (Duroc x White, 250-300 g). The rings were mounted in an organ bath filled with Krebs-Henseleit solution (pH 7.4) maintained at 37°C. The contractile responses were recorded isometrically using a force transducer and a PowerLab data acquisition system (ADInstruments, Colorado, USA). The Krebs-Henseleit solution was continuously gassed with 95% O2 and 5% CO2. The rings were allowed to equilibrate for 30 min before the start of the experiment. The contractile responses were elicited by adding increasing concentrations of histamine (0.01-10 µM) or acetylcholine (0.01-3 mM) to the bath. The contractile responses were expressed as the percentage of the maximum response to histamine or acetylcholine.

